status_notes: Case Closed. Case Resolved. The Boston Public Works Construction Inspection Unit (CIU) Supervisor Mark Cardarelli called the constituent and informed him of the following:. National Grid is installing a new gas main.  The city encourages this type of capital upgrade work.  It will eliminate future emergency repairs. National Grid has to install the gas main first.  Once the main has been installed, then all service connections can be made. If the city were to make National Grid pave to grade each day's trench work,  it would cause multiple seams along the trench.  More importantly, every service connection needs to be cut into the trench. Paving the trench every day would end up with  2 by 2 patches in front of every house inside the paved trench area, resulting in a very poor final product.  In order to have the best final paving, the city allows the utility company to leave the trench down low until all service connections are made and then pave the trench all at once, resulting in a smooth, level final trench repair.  Service laterals are topped within 24 hours of excavation. What the constituent is observing is the trench left down low in preparation for one continuous final paving operation. Mark acknowledges that riding a bike through the work zone could be hazardous and he has ordered the contractor to post signs indicating the trench is down low. The trench is scheduled to be topped by December 19th. Mark Cardarelli. Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance. Boston Public Works Department. 617-635-4951 Office. 617-438-8517 Cell.

status_notes: Case Closed. Case Resolved. The Boston Public Works Construction Inspection Unit (CIU) Supervisor, investigated and determined the following:. BWSC actively replacing old water and sewer mains in the Dudley Sq area. The city highly encourages this type of work. It will eliminate possible future emergency leak repairs. The city acknowledges that the construction will cause an inconvenience to the residents. However in the long run the construction is well worth it. Having a street dug up for emergency repairs soon after paving is frustrating for all. With the new gas main installed, the city can feel extremely comfortable that no embarrassing street cuts will happen if it determines to pave your street in the future. The contractor is required to maintain the pavement markings that are dug up during construction.  As of December 3rd all temporary pavement markings have been restored. Next Springs when BWSC comes back to perform the permanent trench repair thermal plastic will be used to restore the pavement markings. The CIU inspector will monitor the progress of the job. The City apologizes for the inconvenience. Sincerely,. Mark Cardarelli. Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance. Boston Public Works Department. 617-635-4951 Office.
